		<header>
			
			<h1>Senegalese government temporarily removes import restrictions on onions </h1>

			
			<h4>
												11 October 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In August 2013, the Senegalese government decided to review the import ban imposed on onions, which had been in place since February 2013 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Horticulture/Measures-taken-in-Senegal-to-counter-onion-imports-and-support-local-production" target="_blank">Measures taken in Senegal to counter onion imports and support local pro...</a>’, 1 July 2013). The ban had been due to expire at the end of August, but was withdrawn earlier as a result of government concerns over the availability of onions on the local market, following the findings of a market investigation. This was also informed by rising consumer prices and retailer concerns expressed over a possible onion shortage during a period of high demand.</p><p>However, according to a government press report, producers maintained that “there is a sufficient stock to ensure the supply of the market”. Nevertheless, on 31 July 2013, the government decided to release 6,000 tonnes of onions from stocks to ease price pressures, stating that while the government had chosen to protect domestic producers, this should not be at the expense of Senegalese consumers.</p><p>In a linked development, the employers’ trade union of Senegal (the <i>Confédération nationale des employeurs du Sénégal</i>), encouraged by the government, has announced its intention to develop the processing of onion powder, with the aim of dealing with marketing problems of the industry and creating new outlets for domestic onion producers. (4, 5)</p><p>Online press reports indicate that Dutch onion exports to Senegal increased by 60% in the first 6 months of 2013, compared to the first 6 months of 2012 (while total Dutch onion exports increased by 20%). In the same period, exports to Cote d’Ivoire almost doubled, while exports to Mauritania increased by 6%. Exports to Guinea and Sierra Leone, however, fell by 11% for both countries. The period saw a 28% increase in Dutch onion exports to these main West African destinations in the first 6 months of 2013 compared to the corresponding period in 2012, resulting in an increase in the significance of West African markets to the Dutch onion trade.</p><p><b>Onion exports from the Netherlands to selected countries (tonnes)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
