				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The measures adopted in the Senegalese onion sector highlight the difficulties faced by ACP governments in trying to manage markets in ways that meet the needs of all stakeholders (producers, consumers, traders, retailers and processors). At the beginning of 2013, the government of Senegal showed a willingness to protect producers’ interests, however, the imposition of the import ban appears to have given rise to shortages of onions on local markets and an increase in onion prices. It is unclear why this has occurred, given the 60% increase in Dutch onion exports to Senegal reported in the first 6 months of 2013.</p><p>There would appear to be some serious shortcomings in both the application of the ban and the functioning of onion supply chains in Senegal. The government may need to look at the use of alternative policy tools to strengthen the functioning of domestic onion supply chains and regulate the flow of onion imports. There are indications that such a policy rethink is already under way, linked to a new system of import licence allocation (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Agriculture/Commodities/Horticulture/Measures-taken-in-Senegal-to-counter-onion-imports-and-support-local-production" target="_self">Measures taken in Senegal to counter onion imports and support local pro...</a>’, 1 July 2013).</p>
		</div>
		
